<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="32" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,663]" pageId="8" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,318,226,252]" pageId="8" pageNumber="32">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Recognized by the ant-mimetic appearance (
<figureCitation box="[861,934,226,252]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 7" captionStartId="2.[151,278,1615,1639]" captionTargetBox="[292,1293,795,1593]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[292,1294,795,1604]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 7. Habitus views of Acrorrhinium spp. 1. amblyangulum (male); 2. amblyangulum (female); 3. dolichantennatum (male); 4. dolichantennatum (female); 5. hongkong (male); 6. hongkong (female); 7. inexpectatum (male)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196380/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="32">
Fig. 
<number box="[917,934,226,252]" pageId="8" pageNumber="32" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
), the brown coloration of the dorsum with many small irregular spots, the light yellow-brown membrane with its veins distinctly visible, the longitudinal sulcus on the vertex not reaching the posterior margin of the vertex, the elongate spiniform frons with the apex weakly curved and tapering (
<figureCitation box="[492,576,338,364]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,270,1977,2001]" captionTargetBox="[181,1420,976,1960]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[177,1421,964,1982]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 11. Lateral view of head of Acrorrhinium spp. 8. amblyangulum (male); 9. dolichantennatum (male); 10. hongkong (male); 11. inexpectatum (male)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196381/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="32">
Fig. 
<number box="[546,576,338,364]" pageId="8" pageNumber="32" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
), the extremely long labium almost reaching the abdominal segment VII, the head and hemelytra covered with sparse, short, sericeous setae and simple setae, the relatively small scutellum with the central part weakly convex, and the male genitalia: vesica strongly sclerotized, twisted, apex with a slender and bifurcate projection, secondary gonopore well developed (
<figureCitation box="[1116,1203,450,476]" captionStart="FIGURES 24 – 27" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1970,1994]" captionTargetBox="[285,1307,989,1969]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[278,1315,981,1969]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 24 – 27. Male genitalia of Acrorrhinium inexpectatum: 24. Vesica; 25. Left paramere; 26. Right paramere; 27. Phallotheca" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196385/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="32">
Fig. 
<number box="[1170,1203,450,476]" pageId="8" pageNumber="32" value="24.0">24</number>
</figureCitation>
); hypophysis of left paramere slender, weakly curved with apex blunt (
<figureCitation box="[780,873,488,514]" captionStart="FIGURES 24 – 27" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1970,1994]" captionTargetBox="[285,1307,989,1969]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[278,1315,981,1969]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 24 – 27. Male genitalia of Acrorrhinium inexpectatum: 24. Vesica; 25. Left paramere; 26. Right paramere; 27. Phallotheca" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196385/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="32">
Fig. 
<number box="[839,873,488,514]" pageId="8" pageNumber="32" value="25.0">25</number>
</figureCitation>
), right paramere leaflike, lamellate (
<figureCitation box="[1328,1422,488,514]" captionStart="FIGURES 24 – 27" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1970,1994]" captionTargetBox="[285,1307,989,1969]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[278,1315,981,1969]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 24 – 27. Male genitalia of Acrorrhinium inexpectatum: 24. Vesica; 25. Left paramere; 26. Right paramere; 27. Phallotheca" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196385/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="32">
Fig. 
<number box="[1387,1422,488,514]" pageId="8" pageNumber="32" value="26.0">26</number>
</figureCitation>
), phallotheca weakly curved (
<figureCitation box="[503,599,525,551]" captionStart="FIGURES 24 – 27" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1970,1994]" captionTargetBox="[285,1307,989,1969]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[278,1315,981,1969]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 24 – 27. Male genitalia of Acrorrhinium inexpectatum: 24. Vesica; 25. Left paramere; 26. Right paramere; 27. Phallotheca" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196385/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="32">
Fig. 
<number box="[563,599,525,551]" pageId="8" pageNumber="32" value="27.0">27</number>
</figureCitation>
). It is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Distant" authorityName="Distant" box="[877,1144,525,551]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Acrorrhinium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhinoceros">
<emphasis box="[877,1046,525,550]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="32">A. rhinoceros</emphasis>
Distant
</taxonomicName>
in coloration and body appearance, but can be separated from the latter by the form of its spiniform frons and the structure of the male genitalia; spiniform frons of 
<taxonomicName box="[552,710,600,625]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Acrorrhinium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhinoceros">
<emphasis box="[552,710,600,625]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="32">A. rhinoceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
relatively small, short, and blunt.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
